Northampton Priority Tree Planting 2015-2023

Author

Kent S Johnson

Introduction

The Northampton Urban Forestry Commission has identified numerous priority regions for new plantings. This report summarizes 2015-2023 planting in many of the priority regions.

The tree locations in this analysis are approximate, derived by geocoding the tree addresses. This locates most trees on the building at the tree address, rather than in the correct location - typically on the right-of-way.

Of the 2,223 trees planted in this period, this report only considers the 2,112 surviving trees. Location data for the 111 removed trees was not available.

Proximity to downtown centers

The Urban Forestry Commission has identified 356 possible planting locations in the public right-of-way near the Northampton, Florence and Leeds city centers. To date, 130 trees have been planted in the right-of-way or tree belt in these regions.

The downtown areas were further divided into 4-5 sectors. This table summarizes the planting per sector; the map shows the trees planted in each sector.

Main arteries through town

433 trees have been planted on main arteries throughout Northampton including Barrett St, Bridge Rd, Bridge St, Chapel St, Conz St, Damon Rd, Day Ave, Elm St, Elm St, Hatfield St, King St, Locust St, Main St, Florence, Nonotuck St, North Main St, Old South St, Pleasant Street, Prince St, Rocky Hill Rd, Ryan Rd, West St, and Westhampton Rd.

Proximity to low-income neighborhoods

Several low-income areas have been identified for planting including Florence Heights, Grove Street Inn, Hampshire Heights, MacDonald House, Meadowbrook Apts, River Run Apts, and Salvo House and the streets Bridge Rd, Damon Rd, Fruit St, Glendale Rd, Graves Ave, Hawley St, Lane Plant Rd, Main St, Leeds, Market St, and Rust Ave.

104 trees have been planted in these areas:

Environmental Justice populations

The Commonwealth of Massachusetts designates environmental justice populations based on demographic criteria at the census block group level.

643 trees have been planted in environmental justice communities in Northampton.

Heavily trafficked secondary streets

560 trees have been planted on heavily-trafficked secondary streets throughout Northampton.

Neighborhoods with sparse tree cover

146 trees have been planted in neighborhoods identified as having sparse tree cover.
